Subsidy trap
The US - no policy has pitted good economics as directly against good politics as food and energy subsidies.
Unaffordable subsidies are becoming the core issue faced by the three most important new leaders in the world. They are Egyptian President Sisi, Indonesian President "Jokowi" Widodo, and Indian Prime Minister Modi.
Sisi faces a subsidy cut that needs to be better than expected.
On the other hand, Modi is facing an even worse situation than expected, and it may even undermine the long-awaited WTO agreement.
While Jokowi's situation remains unclear.
In July, Sisi achieved a feat that few leaders in North Africa and the Middle East have accomplished: he significantly cut back on long-standing energy subsidies, causing prices to rise by 41-78%.
Notably, almost no protests erupted in opposition.
Egypt's food subsidy program costs over $5 billion annually and urgently needs reform.
Bread prices have remained at an extremely low level, often being fed to animals.
In the past, efforts by North African countries to cut such subsidies often led to unrest and even overthrew governments.
But the Sisi government seems to be making progress in this area as well.
Bread subsidies have been cut by 13%.
Sisi has no other choice.
Even after the subsidy reduction, the current government's budget deficit target for the next fiscal year remains at 10% of GDP (which would be 14% without subsidy reduction).
However, few people expected Sisi, who came to power in a turbulent political environment, to act faster than Modi. Modi won the prime ministership with an overwhelming democratic majority in India, where there is a pressing need for comprehensive economic reform.
In Indonesia, Jokowi, who took office in October, inherited long-standing fuel subsidies worth around $21 billion annually (20% of government spending), which have been a heavy burden on the country.
His predecessor, Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono, took a brave first step a year ago by raising fuel prices.
Jokowi's advisors recommended cutting the remaining subsidies, and he has bluntly stated that he plans to phase them out over four years.
Economists confidently oppose commodity subsidies, as agricultural and energy markets are close to perfect competition, with a large number of consumers on the demand side and a large number of producers on the supply side.
In imperfectly competitive fields, the government — not large private monopolies — is the root of the problem.
Critics of the invisible hand point out that self-regulating private markets may fail in various ways.
For instance, income inequality and environmental externalities are the two main reasons for government intervention.
What sparks sharp controversy about food and fossil fuel subsidies is that they are often implemented under the guise of environmental or egalitarian goals, but in reality, they achieve little to nothing for these goals and often have the opposite effect.
In Egypt, food subsidies provide less than 20% to the poor.
Most oil subsidies in other countries have enriched the middle class, while the poor rely on walking or public transportation.
In India, less than 0.1% of liquefied petroleum gas subsidies went to the poorest population, while 52.6% flowed into the pockets of the richest group.
Globally, less than 20% of fossil fuel subsidies went to the poorest 20% of the population.
Food and energy subsidies can also distort public policy, and Modi's government, which protects Indian agricultural subsidies, is a clear example.
In fact, Modi's government vetoed the WTO compromise that would have been the most important progress in multilateral trade talks over the past decade, rendering it null and void.
Agricultural subsidies sometimes benefit producers generously and consumers indirectly, especially in poor countries; at other times, they benefit consumers generously and producers indirectly, especially in rich countries.
India's policy aims to achieve both.
As a result, India has achieved a feat: providing wheat to consumers at subsidized prices, while also experiencing over-supply because farmers can sell at higher prices.
(Farmers also receive subsidies for agricultural inputs – electricity, water, and fertilizers – which has led to environmental degradation.)
The government has purchased large quantities of rotten wheat and rice, and the distribution of the small portion that reaches consumers is corrupt and does not align with the goal of helping the poor.
The government may continue to maintain subsidies and stockpiling.
But it knows that this will violate WTO rules.
Since it is impossible to permanently change these rules, Modi simply vetoed the Trade Facilitation Agreement, which the WTO had been eagerly expecting.
Once subsidies are implemented, it is difficult to take them back.
When world commodity prices rise (as they did over the past decade), citizens accustomed to market-determined domestic prices are more likely to accept the reality that officials cannot isolate them from the shock.
But people accustomed to government-set prices for food and energy will demand that the government take responsibility.
This provides a strong reason for not implementing subsidies in the first place.
However, this does not mean that once subsidies are implemented, maintaining them is always the best choice for shrewd politicians.
If the alternative to price hikes is shortages or rationing, angry opponents may also erupt.
Similarly, if the growing gap ultimately leads to higher retail prices, even slow-moving leaders will not benefit.
In an ideal situation, while reducing food and energy subsidies, other more efficient measures to support lower-income individuals should be taken.
Developing countries have experience with effective transfer mechanisms, such as Mexico's Progresa-Oportunidades program and Brazil's Bolsa Família conditional cash transfer policy, as well as India's Unique Identification system and other technological innovations.
However, some countries only adjust when a budget crisis arrives, and they may not have the money for transfers to alleviate the pain.
Smart politicians might implement unpopular adjustments at the beginning of their term.
Jokowi and Yingsak have taken this approach.
While Modi, who won a landslide election with the slogan of market reform, has fallen behind.
